</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><title>True Cost of Government -- ATR</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="cal.gif"
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+3><FONT SIZE=+4>T</FONT>rue<FONT SIZE=+4>C</FONT>ost of <FONT SIZE=+4>G</FONT>overnment <BR><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+4>D</FONT>ay is<FONT SIZE=+4>  J</FONT>uly</FONT><FONT SIZE=+4> 9th</FONT><HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=80%><address>by Alan L. Philp</address></CENTER><P>
	By April 15 in most years or April 17 this year, you have filed your tax returns. Maybe you think you are finished with your obligations to Uncle Sam and  now you can enjoy the fruits of your labor for the rest of the year. Right?<P>
	Not so fast. The taxes you paid are really only the visible tip of a much larger iceberg whose deadly mass remains hidden from view. The bulk of these hidden costs come from deficit spending and added costs to all goods and services which are generated by government regulations.<P>
	 The costs are real, they are just not easy to see.  That's no accident.  For years liberal legislators and activist bureaucrats have used stealth budgets to push the growth of government and mushroom federal spending. When hidden regulatory costs are added to the burdens of direct taxes, the price tag is staggering.<P>
	Consider the 12-month calendar.  If you started working on January 1, you would have to work all the way to July 9, more than half the year, to pay for  costs of both taxes and regulations.  Only then, five days after Independence Day,  are you able to start keeping your hard-earned money for your own needs.<P>
  	Imagine America's founders rolling in their graves at the thought of Americans placed in involuntary servitude to their own government until after July 4. Today's government, with its ferocious appetite for taxpayer dollars, eats away at our economic liberty.  The federal tax system of 1995 makes the English Parliament's Stamp Act of 1765, the Townshend Acts and tea duties of 1767, and the Intolerable Acts of 1774 all combined look miniscule in comparison.<P>
	For many years, the Tax Foundation calculated "Tax Freedom Day" as the theoretical calendar day that taxpayers stop working to pay direct taxes.  This year, Tax Freedom Day is May 6.<P>
  	But almost every year since 1969, the federal government has spent several percentage points of GNP more than it takes in from taxes. "Spending Freedom Day" therefore is a date still later (May 16) which marks the day Uncle Sam stops spending the combined earnings of all citizens.  Right now, the national debt has a huge impact on the budget.  Three percent of GNP must be devoted just to pay interest on the debt.  That's more money for interest than for national defense.<P>
	But Tax Freedom Day and Spending Freedom Day don't fully measure the true burden that Washington imposes on citizens.  Why?  Because regulations generated by federal agencies drive up the prices of everything produced or sold in America including services.  The extra money and human resources businesses must spend to comply with regulations is just as much a financial burden on consumers as direct taxes.<P>
   	In 1993, Americans for Tax Reform Foundation originated the idea of calculating the additional days that Americans had to work to pay for regulations beyond Tax Freedom Day and called it "Cost of Government Day."   The purpose of Cost of Government Day is to help people understand the true cost of government's tax and regulatory burden combined.<P>
 	Cost of Government Day is the total percentage of Net National Product consumed by government spending and estimated total regulatory costs.  Government spending is projected in the president's budget forecast.  A reasonable estimate of federal regulatory costs can be made from a 1992 study by Rochester Institute of Technology Professor Thomas Hopkins.<P>
 	This year, July 9 is Cost of Government Day.  That is the date beyond Tax Freedom Day that Americans have earned enough in gross income to pay off their share of government-imposed financial obligations.  It moves later in the year as government spending and hidden taxes increase.<P>
	For two years, we have been paying for President Clinton's 1993 tax hikes.  Every time we buy gasoline we pay higher excise taxes.  Every time we buy groceries or clothing, we pay the so-called "millionaire's" tax.  That tax was supposed to "soak the rich" but really hit small business operators who file personal income taxes rather than corporate income taxes.<P>
	State and local taxes have also increased due to Clinton administration policies.  Unfunded federal mandates and regulations imposed by past Congresses or activist bureaucrats have forced state or local government to spend more money and raise taxes to pay for the mandate.<P>
 	For example, in 1970, Illinois was a leader among states that designed special education programs for children with developmental disabilities.  The programs are costly.  But citizens of that state supported spending money to make sure children with special needs were offered as many educational opportunities as circumstances permitted.<P>
	But Congress took a good idea and ran amok with the passage of Public Law 94-142.  Opportunities became "rights" which imposed massive costs on local school districts all over the country.  Federal regulations made it nearly impossible for school administrators to make common-sense distinctions between special educational costs and purely medical ones.  School boards began to ask if it is really fair that a single student with special needs could cost a district more than $100,000 per year without federal reimbursement that Congress promised when the law passed.<P>
	This pattern of political excess permeates everything Congress did for decades from unjustified increases in federal deposit insurance to unjustified micromanagement of the Americans with Disabilities Act.  Mayor Gregory S. Lashutka of Columbus, Ohio, describes unfunded mandates this way:  "It's like having your Uncle Sam take you to lunch, order your food, and then hand you the check."<P>
	But by far the most expensive silent taxes are federal regulations and unfunded mandates on private business.  In 1993 and 1994, President Clinton's allies in Congress approved a towering stack of new regulations.   The new rules combined with all previous regulations, cost Americans more than $700 billion, or $2,800 per person, in 1994.<P>
	But we should count our blessings.  Had the Clinton administration's 1993 plan for a national health care system become law, Cost of Government Day would be approximately one month later.  We would be working for government well into August.<P>
	In November, 1994, a decisive majority of voters asked for change in the direction Congress has traveled for decades.  Much of that desire for change was fueled by citizens who believed the burden of mandates on state and local governments and regulations on private employers has become far too heavy compared to the benefits that those regulations were supposed to realize.<P>
 	Much evidence suggests the regulatory revolt which shook ballot boxes last November has plenty of steam left. California, for example, faces a ticking time bomb.  Golden State voters are circulating petitions for a hugely popular initiative that would eliminate affirmative action regulations and save the state billions of dollars every year.  Affirmative action programs were originally designed to redress past unjustified discrimination in society at large.  But many have evolved as a system which awards jobs, contracts, scholarships, and academic degrees by arbitrary quotas based on gender or racial identification rather than on merit or qualifications of an applicant.   The nationwide costs of affirmative action programs are estimated at $25 billion per year.<P>
	Indirect costs (not included in Cost of Government Day) of filling out paperwork, reorganizing the workplace, and lost time are in excess of $100 billion per year, according to a 1993 Forbes magazine estimate.   Consider some other examples of regulatory excess which concern voters:
1. Last September, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service relied on a one-paragraph petition by a botanist at the University of California, Davis, to declare three varieties of "fairy shrimp" in Sacramento to be an "endangered" species.  Even though millions of the hardy shrimp are found in irrigation ditches and ponds in California, Europe, Asia, Australia, and Africa, the "endangered" designation caused the closing of a pony ranch that housed a program for needy and disabled children.  The action could cost the Sacramento housing industry $500 million.<P>
2. The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) is using the 1990 Clean Air Act to create the Employee Commute Option (ECO).  This regulation mandates companies with more than 100 employees located in high-smog urban areas to force a percentage of workers to use carpools.  Violations can cost $25,000 each.  As Eric Peters, an automotive writer for <ADDRESS>The Washington Times</ADDRESS> noted, "The real genius of the ECO mandate is that it turns employers-not the government or the EPA-into the bullyboy."<P>
3. Republican congressional leaders and California initiative backers are leading a national crusade to rein in the cost of lawsuits.  Tort settlements cost the nation at least $150 billion per year.  Creighton Hale, CEO of Little League Baseball, wrote in The Wall Street Journal about a volunteer coach who was sued for pain, suffering, and punitive damages after one of his outfielders was beaned by a pop fly.  A Girl Scouts of America spokesperson told the newspaper that the Scouts must sell 87,000 boxes of cookies annually to pay liability premiums.  So far, the Clinton administration has no plan for major tort reform.  Some observers speculate that Clinton policy could be influenced by the fact that individual trial lawyers donated $470,000 to the president's 1992 primary campaign, according to a CNN report.  Trial lawyers, many of whom collect large percentages of tort case settlement fees, are strongly opposed to any caps on jury awards.<P>
 	The best hope for reversing the damage done by excess spending and regulatory programs is a fully informed citizenry which understands the true costs that regulations impose on their lives.  One of the first bills in the Contract with America to pass the new Congress was one to make it more difficult for Congress to impose unfunded mandates on states without careful economic-impact studies and guarantees of federal money to reimburse state costs.  President Clinton has signed this new law.  The unfunded mandates law should have the impact of slowing down thoughtless federal regulations.<P>
  	Other reforms on the GOP congressional agenda include tort reform, slowing the rate of yearly increases in spending, regulatory reform, property rights protections, pension reform, and returning powers and duties for certain programs back to the states.  When fully implemented, these reforms could move Cost of Government Day earlier in the year by several weeks.	A national consensus needs to determine how much of the fruits of our labor we are willing to surrender to support government.<P>
<P>
<CENTER><a href="/atr/bar.map"><img src="/atr/bar.gif" ismap border="0"></a> </CENTER>
 <P> 
</FONT><ADDRESS><A HREF="MAILTO:atr@townhall.com">Americans for Tax Reform</A><FONT SIZE=3><BOLD> 
