<HTML>
<HEAD><title>Front Lines -- ATR</title></HEAD>
<BODY Bgcolor=#FFFFFF><CENTER><a href="/atr/bar4.map"><img src="/atr/bar4.gif" ismap border="0"></a>  </CENTER>
<BOLD><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>


|<a href="#rock">Rock the House!</a>| <BR>
|<a href="#court">Court Blocks Term Limits</a>|</bold></center></font><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100%>
<FONT SIZE=+1><BOLD>Grover Appears on Donahue<FONT><BOLD><P>

<A NAME="Donuhue">	Americans for Tax Reform Foundation (ATRF) President Grover Norquist was a guest on Phil Donahue's TV show on May 26.  Norquist appeared with Richardson Foundation President Heather Higgins, former TV actor Ben Jones, and Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.) to discuss how Congress has changed under the new House Speaker, Rep. Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.)<P>
	Jones, a frequent Gingrich political rival and critic, played the part of a Deputy Sheriff named "Cooter" on a 1980's TV series called <ADDRESS>The Dukes of Hazzard.</ADDRESS>  In the wide-ranging discussion, the usually boisterous Phil Donahue audience almost could not get a word in edgewise since the panelists' debate was so lively.<P>
	Hard and fast conclusions are hard to reach in the Donahue format, but few viewers were surprised to hear that Norquist and Higgins found great merit in the first 100 days of the Gingrich speakership whereas Rep. Frank and Ben Jones were quite grumpy about the direction of the new Congress.  Stay tuned.<P></a><CENTER><a href="/atr/bar4.map"><img src="/atr/bar4.gif" ismap border="0"></a>  </CENTER><p>



<FONT SIZE=+1><bold><a name="rock">  Rock the House!</a></center></bold><FONT></p>

	Early July marks the publication of Rock the House, a new book by ATRF President Grover G. Norquist which puts the 1994 elections under a microscope.  With an initial press run of one million copies, Rock the House is certain to become the definitive explanation of how the old Roosevelt Coalition unraveled and was replaced by a conservative coalition as the governing majority in America.<P>
	Norquist believes the Contract with America was central to what happened last November, and he sees it as a model for future politics in America.  The Contract produced an honest connection between campaign promises and policy fulfillment that is all too rare in any election.  People knew what they were voting for, and they now have a standard against which to measure the performance of the elected.<P>
	Rock the House examines the pluses and minuses of the Reagan, Bush, and Clinton administrations and provides a road map for the future. Watch for Rock the House in bookstores this summer. Visa and Mastercard customers may call 1-800-201-7625 to order your copy for $9.65 plus $1.50 for shipping and handling.<P>

<CENTER><a href="/atr/bar4.map"><img src="/atr/bar4.gif" ismap border="0"></a>  </CENTER><p>

<FONT SIZE=+1><bold><a name="court">Court Blocks Term Limits</bold></FONT></a><p></center>

<p>
 	The U.S. Supreme Court decided on May 22 by a 5 to 4 decision that Arkansas and 22 other states could not limit the terms of members of Congress from those states.  Justice John Paul Stevens  wrote an 88-page opinion which devoted a great deal of space to the merits of term limits as a public policy.  That is somewhat unusual since the merits of the policy should not have been an issue before the court, only the power of the states to decide the policy for themselves.  In dissent, Justice Clarence Thomas stated that the Constitution was silent on the question of whether or not states could determine limits for the terms of its members of the U.S. House and Senate.<P>
	The 22nd Amendment was passed by Congress in 1947 and ratified in 1951. Beginning with President Dwight Eisenhower, that amendment set a limit of two four-year terms for president.  Before that time, the Constitution was silent on limiting the president's term and every president except Franklin D. Roosevelt chose to seek no more than eight years in office.<P>
	The Supreme Court decision seems to close the door on all state and federal legislation on term limits which leaves a constitutional amendment as the only remaining option. A vote in the House in April to limit terms by constitutional amendment was part of the GOP Contract with America.  But backers failed by 61 votes to attain the necessary two-thirds majority.<P>
   		Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole (R-Kan.) has stated the Senate will likely vote on a constitutional amendment this summer. Public opinion polls show 75 to 80 percent of Americans favor term limits.  The decision did not upset term limits for state and local offices.  National and state term limits organizations are planning now to make term limits an issue in the 1996 elections.<P>
<CENTER><a href="/atr/bar4.map"><img src="/atr/bar4.gif" ismap border="0"></a>  </CENTER>
