<P><blockquote>
<CENTER><h3>Taxes a Decisive Factor in '96 <font color="#ffOOOO"><i>Hill Alert</font></i></h3><p>
<b>
Publication Notices; Issue Updates
</b> 
<P>
OCTOBER 28, 1996<p>
ISSUE NO.22<p>
<hr>
<P>
<b>Update on a Few Issues<BR>
</b></center><P>
"With high taxes and a burdensome tax system impeding the
growth and survival of small businesses, taxes will be a priority
for each and every small business person who votes on November
5," said Small Business Survival Committee (SBSC) President
Karen Kerrigan.
<P>
Kerrigan made her remarks on Capitol Hill  at a press conference
supporting the <I><B>Taxpayer Protection Pledge</B></I> -- an
effort sponsored by Americans for Tax Reform (ATR), a 60,000 member
national taxpayer organization.
<P>
"In 1992 Bill Clinton promised a middle-class tax cut, instead
middle-class small business owners got hit with the biggest tax
increase in history.  President Clinton made a campaign promise
to cut taxes, instead he raised them.  The <I><B>Pledge</B></I>
separates the true friend of the taxpayer from the big tax-and-spenders,"
said Kerrigan.
<P>
There are 2 versions of the <I>Taxpayer Protection Pledge</I>:
state and federal.  Signers of the state pledge promise to oppose
and vote against <U>any and all</U> efforts to increase taxes
while federal pledge signers promise to oppose increases in marginal
income tax rates and reductions or elimination of deductions and
credit.
<P>
 To date, GOP Presidential candidate Bob Dole, Libertarian Presidential
candidate Harry Browne, 210 U.S. House of Representatives, 35
U.S. Senators, and over 700 candidates or incumbents for state
legislators have signed the pledge.  
<P>
To find out if your congressional candidate has signed the pledge,
contact SBSC at 800-223-7526 or visit the ATR home page at <B>www.atr.org</B>.
 
<P>
The text of the federal Taxpayer Protection Pledge is below.<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><I>Americans for Tax Reform<BR>
</I></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><U><I><B>Taxpayer Protection Pledge<BR>
</B></I></U></CENTER>
<P>
<I>I, ______________, pledge to the taxpayers of the United States,
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>and to the American people that I will<BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>ONE, oppose any and all efforts to increase the marginal <BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>income tax rates for individuals and/or businesses; and<BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>TWO, oppose any further reduction or elimination of <BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>deductions and credits, unless matched dollar for dollar by
further <BR>
</I>
<P>
<I>reducing tax rates.<BR>
</I>
<P>
 If Congress Changes Hands<BR>

<P>
The media continues to speculate about Democrats regaining control
of the Congress.  While SBSC believes that it<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">?</FONT>Newt<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
gavel<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT> in the 105th
Congress, we did speculate on how small business issues would
fare under a Democrat House majority.
<P>
Below you will find  Democrat members who would assume leadership
positions if the House changed party hands, as well as the ranking
minority member of each committee that would assume chairmanship.
 We then matched each individual to their current SBSC rating.
 
<P>
The average score of these Democrat House members is 2.6% out
of 100% <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">C</FONT> a score which
earns them SBSC<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">?</FONT>Betrayer
of Small Business<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT> designation.
 House chairmen in the 104th Congress average 86.4% earning them
the <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">?</FONT>Friend of Small
Business<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT> designation.
<BR>

<P>
Name   Current Position   SBSC Rating
<P>
