<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Environmentalism for a Dynamic World: 1996 -- PFF</TITLE>


</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000">
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<br><br>
<h2>Environmentalism for a Dynamic World</h2>
</B>
<P>
<CENTER><B>By Lynn Scarlett</B><BR>
</CENTER>
<br>
<small>
<a href="#vision">The "Vision Thing"</a><br>
<a href="#values">Values</a><br>
<a href="#knowledge">The Knowledge Problem</a><br>
<a href="#firm">The Individual, the Firm and the Marketplace</a><br>
<a href="#reform">Principles of Reform</a><br>
<a href="#do">What Can Policymakers Do?</a><br>
<a href="#better">A Better Future</a><br>
</small>
<P>
The mood was euphoric. The tone one of bravado. &quot;We're looking
for horror stories. We're going to change the way things are done
around here!&quot; Thus spoke one Congressman shortly after the
November 1994 election. The targets? The Endangered Species Act,
the Clean Air Act, the Clean Water Act, all environmental regulations,
and especially the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA).<BR>

<P>
By 1996, the mood was sober; the tone confused. Congressional
reformers of the 104th Congress had failed to institute hoped-for
changes in environmental regulations. &quot;The stumbling block
to reform,&quot; admitted a Congressional staffer at a January
1996 retreat, &quot;is the vision thing&quot; - how reformers
define and understand basic environmental policy challenges.<BR>

<P>
What is needed is an environmental vision that combines an appreciation
of the general environmental psyche of the nation with a respect
for the diverse values people hold. This means finding approaches
to environmental problems that economize on the need for consensus
- that limit instances in which non-voluntary collective decisions
are sought - while reinforcing incentives for personal environmental
stewardship. <BR>

<P>
Reformers also need a plausible picture of how the world works
- how one identifies environmental problems, assembles information
relevant to minimizing these problems and maintains incentives
- within firms and among individuals - to apply that information.
<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><a name="vision"></a><B>The &quot;Vision Thing&quot;<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
The &quot;old vision&quot; that shaped the past quarter-century
of environmental policies offered lofty images of Mother Nature
and a better world. Its language of poetry - and sometimes fear
- captivated the imagination of the American public. And, translated
into public policies, the old vision produced some successes.
<BR>

<P>
But, as Horatio warned Hamlet, &quot;All is not well.&quot; The
record of environmental gains tells only part of the environmental
story. The rest of the story - high costs and growing conflict
- are the driving forces behind appeals for environmental policy
reform. Three features of the old vision made high conflict and
high costs a likely outcome.<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><a name="values"></a><B>Values<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
First is the matter of values. The old environmental vision often
implicitly, and sometimes explicitly, portrayed environmental
values as absolute - as somehow more important than other values.
The result has been an endorsement of &quot;zero emission&quot;
goals and remediation standards in which little consideration
is given to costs. &quot;If Mother Nature didn't put it in,&quot;
one California regulator recently told me, &quot;you had to take
it out - everything - that was the goal. This drove us to rigid,
grossly exuberant attempts at clean up.&quot;<BR>

<P>
But this view that environmental values are absolute cannot be
right. Environmental values, while important, are situated among
a cluster of values that constitute quality-of-life. People seek
health, safety, nourishment, shelter, learning, companionship,
aesthetic enrichment and personal accomplishment, along with environmental
protections. And it is often difficult for outsiders - or even
individuals themselves - to know in advance how they would prefer
to trade off among different wants.<BR>

<P>
Most people want all good things, including environmental protection.
Year after year, opinion polls demonstrate (at least in the abstract)
a commitment to environmental values. Any successful reform effort
must appreciate this commitment.<BR>

<P>
But general societal trends do not erase particular differences
among individuals. Environmental values are more important for
some people than for others. And, for any particular individual,
some environmental values are more important than others. A new
environmental vision must depart from the old way of thinking
by recognizing the need to find ways in which individuals and
particular communities can undertake their own balancing among
these many values.<BR>

<P>
Environmental problem-solving is about making choices. The challenge,
however, is not simply one of deciding what's to be done. The
challenge is also one of determining &quot;who should decide&quot;
and &quot;how.&quot; Recognizing that people have diverse values
establishes one constraint in thinking about &quot;who shall decide.&quot;
<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><a name="knowledge"></a><B>The Knowledge Problem<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
A second constraint is what Nobel laureate F.A. Hayek called the
&quot;knowledge problem&quot; - how societies create and access
information relevant to making decisions about the allocation
of time and resources. <BR>

<P>
The old vision viewed the information challenge as one of identifying
general environmental problems and then specifying uniform remedies
to those problems. Information relevant to environmental problem-solving
was perceived to be the sort that could be collected and centralized
within an agency of experts, then translated into a series of
one-size-fits-all regulations that prescribed acceptable technologies,
clean-up methods and single-purpose wilderness management plans.
The result was often an attitude that &quot;bureaucrats know best.&quot;
<BR>

<P>
This old vision was partly right about &quot;knowledge.&quot;
Many environmental problems do involve matters of &quot;general
knowledge&quot; - scientific understanding of facts that are constant
across time and space. Sometimes this scientific knowledge is
a matter of settled understanding: the boiling point of water,
for instance, or the bonding patterns of chemicals. EPA uses this
kind of knowledge to develop ways of detecting chemical concentrations
in polluted soils. <BR>

<P>
In other instances, scientific knowledge is a matter of ongoing
research and scientific contention: What, for example, are the
health hazards of various substances or the effects of carbon
dioxide on climate? Or is concentration of a chemical in the soil
a useful indicator of risk to humans and ecosystems? Much environmental
debate takes place over issues of general knowledge, and these
questions are important. But they are not the whole story.<BR>

<P>
Environmental problems and problem-solving also often involve
what Hayek called &quot;specific knowledge&quot; - the knowledge
of time, place and experience. This information varies by circumstance
and location and may change over time. Specific knowledge is decentralized
- it resides on the factory floor, on a specific farm and at a
particular Superfund site.<BR>

<P>
The impacts of a landfill in the desert will differ from those
near the Florida Everglades. Whether incorporating recycled content
into a package optimizes resource efficiency will depend on the
material, the availability of alternative materials, particular
production processes and other product-specific details. Using
two coats of oil-based paint will have different impacts than
using just one coat.<BR>

<P>
These kinds of details do not reside in the minds of bureaucrats
in Washington - or even within state agencies. Yet this is the
kind of knowledge that is often most relevant to understanding
specific environmental problems and the merits of different remedies.
<BR>

<P>
The narrow framing of the &quot;knowledge problem&quot; captured
in the regulatory reform bills proposed in the early part of the
104th Congress did not address this problem of dynamic and decentralized
information. The first prong of the &quot;knowledge problem&quot;
- how to better incorporate available general knowledge into public
policy - dominated that debate. Proponents of the 1995 regulatory
reform bills viewed the essential problem as one of irrationality.
They called for more professionalism and better planners. The
Big Fix, they argued, would come from the twin icons of rationalism:
hard science and good economics.<BR>

<P>
This emphasis on costs and the denunciation of regulations directed
at trivial risks is common sense stuff. An effort to introduce
better science and economic analysis into environmental decision-making
may yield more efficient and sensible policies.<BR>

<P>
But matters of high cost and poorly chosen goals are really derivative
problems. They are a predictable (and lamentable) product of a
mismatch between top-down, micromanaging decision processes and
the world as it is: complex, dynamic and full of particulars rather
than generalities.<BR>

<P>
A reform agenda that simply superimposes cost-benefit decision
constraints on regulators does not get at the kinds of information
problems inherent in a complex, dynamic world full of location-specific
details. Attending to the knowledge problem means, instead, thinking
about what institutions and decision-making processes will create
information feedback loops and facilitate access to relevant knowledge
of time, place, and experience.<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><a name="firm"></a><B>The Individual, the Firm and the Marketplace<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
This challenge brings us to the third feature of the old environmental
vision - its perception of the individual, the firm and the marketplace.
The old vision viewed industry and economic dynamism as a central
cause of environmental degradation. Pollution was not just a problem;
it was evil. And the motives of participants in this economic
growth dynamo were suspect. <BR>

<P>
This view is a recipe for emphasizing sticks, not carrots. It
is also a recipe for emphasizing fines and punishment rather than
problem-solving.<BR>

<P>
As journalist Gregg Easterbrook shows in <B>A Moment on Earth</B>,
his 1,000-plus pages tome on environmental progress, our air and
water are cleaner; wolves again prowl in once-abandoned forests;
and, ospreys fish in once-polluted waters. Easterbrook implicitly
attributes most of these reported gains to three decades of regulation.
Forgotten by Easterbrook and most other chroniclers of environmental
gains is the role that marketplace ingenuity, market prices and
private stewardship have played in environmental progress. This
myopia means the reform agenda has been mostly about fine-tuning
regulations, not rethinking the nation's basic approach to environmentalism.
<BR>

<P>
Yet the incentives promoted by a competitive marketplace have
yielded phenomenal improvements in how efficiently we use resources.
In an essay on technology and environment, Jesse Ausubel reports
that the telecommunications industry now consumes 65 pounds of
silica to create a cable that can carry 1,000 times more messages
than cable made from one ton of copper. A handful of sand versus
a ton of copper represents an environmental triumph of a competitive
marketplace that nudges manufacturers to use less stuff.<BR>

<P>
These trends have occurred in things both great and small. On
the one hand are construction-industry gains, where technology
improvements mean builders can use one-third the materials once
needed to build a high-rise building. At the other end of the
spectrum is the diminutive soda can. In the 1960s, producers required
164 pounds of metal to produce 1,000 soda cans; today they use
around 33 pounds of metal.<BR>

<P>
These gains result not only in &quot;doing more with less.&quot;
They also reduce the &quot;environmental footprint&quot; - the
pollution and waste - associated with producing a given product.
<BR>

<P>
This picture of progress is, of course, imperfect. Two decades
of economic literature have described the &quot;tragedy of the
commons,&quot; in which resources are &quot;owned&quot; by everyone
and thus are essentially owned by no one, since they can be used
indiscriminately by everyone. Under these circumstances, each
person has an incentive to consume as much as possible, as fast
as possible, rather than preserve and protect resources for future
use.<BR>

<P>
This &quot;tragedy of the commons&quot; applies to unowned lands;
it also applies to air basins, oceans and many other water bodies.
<BR>

<P>
Sometimes, the resolution to these commons problems lies in clarifying
rights and strengthening markets, as some environmental economists
have argued for twenty years - occasionally successfully. Environmental
writer Tom Wolf describes a &quot;Ranching for Wildlife&quot;
program in Colorado that borrows from the ideas of these environmental
economists. In the Sangre de Cristo Mountains, elk on public and
private lands compete with cattle for forage. The challenge, suggests
Wolf, is &quot;to figure out how ranchers can capture value from
the elk.&quot;<BR>

<P>
Hunters will pay as much as $8,000 for a license to hunt trophy
elk. But until Colorado passed its Ranching for Wildlife law,
landowners were unable to take part in potential revenues from
the sale of hunting licenses. Under Ranching for Wildlife, the
state still &quot;owns&quot; the wildlife, but owners of large
ranches can auction off a designated number of hunting licenses
that guarantee trophy elk. The program, in effect, has partially
privatized elk-hunting rights. Participating ranch owners now
manage their lands to provide suitable habitat for elk. They also
vigilantly guard against poaching of young bull elk.<BR>

<P>
But some problems - and many air pollution problems fall into
this category - are not easily divisible into private &quot;spheres
of stewardship.&quot; And one person's choices directly affect
others. These problems involve situations in which defining and
enforcing individual rights are costly. These high &quot;transactions
costs,&quot; as economist Ronald Coase called them, inhibit the
emergence of contractual arrangements in which all affected parties
voluntarily work out an allocation of rights and responsibilities.
<BR>

<P>
Thinking about the problems of indivisibility and transaction
costs introduces a central challenge for environmental reform.
Fully private, individual decisions are not always possible. Regulatory
decisions are often undesirable, since they suppress localized
information and impose a single-value hierarchy. And reliance
on courts to resolve all disputes about pollution and other social
&quot;nuisances&quot; can be divisive and costly. Needed is a
way of sorting out which collective decision-making arrangements,
under which circumstances, enhance expression of environmental
values at least cost. <BR>

<P>
The old environmental vision fostered passage of command-and-control
laws that gave scant attention to costs and regulated large and
small problems indiscriminately. That vision nurtured laws that
stirred up adversarial relationships between regulators and the
regulated. It formed the basis for a blueprint destined to divide
communities.<BR>

<P>
A new environmental vision must be compatible with a complex,
dynamic world in which quality-of-life comprises many values,
but time and resources, at any given moment, are not infinite.
Under this vision, environmental values are viewed as part of
an array of wants people hold. This vision also appreciates the
importance of decentralized information - information of time,
place and experience - and recognizes that marketplace institutions
(clearly defined rights, competition and market prices) help foster
incentives for stewardship and efficient resource use. But this
vision also recognizes that all environmental problems are not
alike. Some problems are amenable to some form of &quot;privatized&quot;
solution; others require collective - though not necessarily government
- action.<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><a name="reform"></a><B>Principles of Reform<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
How might the vision outlined here reshape U.S. environmental
policy? The &quot;vision thing&quot; in itself is not enough to
provide direction to an environmental reform agenda. From that
vision, reformers need to outline some simple policy principles.
Five policy principles are consistent with the vision outlined
here. <BR>

<P>
<I>Principle of Decentralization</I>. For three decades, we have
thrust many environmental decisions into the Federal arena. But
for some problems, impacts are strictly local and narrowly circumscribed.
Other environmental problems may impose regional, or even global
impacts. The locus of impact of a problem should help determine
where decision-making authority ought to reside.<BR>

<P>
If most knowledge relevant to understanding specific environmental
problems is location-specific and dynamic, decisions about &quot;how
clean is clean&quot; and what remedies to use should take place
closest to where the problem occurs. For air-emission problems,
that might mean a local air basin. For decisions about cleaning
up an industrial site, that might mean creating processes that
foster bargaining between landowners adjacent to the site and
the site owner. <BR>

<P>
Decentralized bargaining approaches bring to bear relevant local
information. These approaches may also be less likely to drive
decisions toward &quot;zero risk&quot; than centralized decision
processes. In decentralized bargaining situations, citizens face
<I>both</I> the risks associated with a facility and enjoy directly
the benefits - in the form of lower clean-up costs and more job-creation,
for example - associated with a particular remedy. Bargaining
thus serves as a discovery process, revealing more accurate information
about risks and benefits.<BR>

<P>
Unbounded fears may, in fact, be more likely to drive decisions
toward &quot;zero risk&quot; in centralized decision processes.
There, the costs of decisions are spread over an entire population,
but benefits from pursuing pristine clean-ups are enjoyed by those
few near a particular site. The few then have an incentive to
lobby for those benefits, while the many have little incentive
to lobby at all - with obvious results.<BR>

<P>
The contrast between costly Superfund site clean-ups, which have
occurred in a top-down, regulatory framework directed by the EPA,
and more recent local remediation of abandoned industrial sites
through negotiated settlements offers testament to this point.
The locally negotiated clean-ups have, in general, been accomplished
at a fraction of the cost for Superfund sites.<BR>

<P>
<I>Principle of Flexibility</I>. Complexity and change characterize
nature and human interaction with it. Traditional regulations
that prescribe technologies or mandate particular clean-up remedies
ignore location-specific and ever-changing information critical
to all production and consumption decisions. To take advantage
of the knowledge residing within a particular plant, or at a specific
hazardous waste site, or on an individual farm, environmental
policies need to foster flexibility, often through the market
process. Performance standards, in contrast to command-and-control
regulations, allow individuals and firms to figure out how best
to achieve the stated standards (to lower overall air pollution
to a certain level, for instance).<BR>

<P>
<I>Principle of Problem-solving</I>. The old environmental vision
tended to cast business against environmentalists, the private-sector
against the public sector, regulators against the regulated. The
result was an emphasis on crimes and punishment. According to
EPA Administrator Carol Browner, in fiscal year 1994 the EPA collected
$165.2 million in monetary penalties and $747.5 million in injunctive
relief. The agency pursued 2,246 enforcement actions in a single
year - and these efforts do not include state and local government
enforcement activities.<BR>

<P>
Enforcement efforts, per se, are not unwarranted. But an emphasis
on enforcement that leads to prosecutions of sometimes trivial
procedural violations is costly - and such efforts may inhibit
rather than foster actual environmental improvements. An emphasis
on criminal enforcement even when there is no intent to violate
the law or no gross negligence simply expends scarce dollars on
prosecutions rather than problem-solving.<BR>

<P>
A reform agenda needs to foster information exchanges and technology
development, and bolster incentives of individuals - acting alone
and within public and private institutions - to find ways of mitigating
environmental problems.<BR>

<P>
<I>Principle of Balancing.</I> Enhancing quality-of-life requires
optimizing among the many values that people hold. All production
and consumption activities produce residuals. For every residual
generated, some corresponding benefit (from the perspective of
individual consumers) is produced. And all production and consumption
activities involve a series of trade-offs. A dollar spent on pollution
prevention technologies or clean-up is a dollar not available
to invest in other productivity-enhancing endeavors.<BR>

<P>
Trade-offs are not merely between environmental and economic goals.
Many trade-offs are between one set of risks and other risks.
For example, pesticide run-off may contaminate waters, but pesticides
help reduce food spoilage in the field. And less food spoilage
means less food needs to be planted to meet the same consumption
requirements. <BR>

<P>
The September 1995 issue of <I>Risk in Perspective</I>, published
by the Harvard Center for Risk Analysis, reported that &quot;chlorination
of drinking water is considered one of the most dramatic success
stories in the field of public health.&quot; Chlorination has
helped prevent a whole range of waterborne diseases from chronic
diarrhea to typhoid fever. On the other hand, the Harvard newsletter
cautions that &quot;chlorination is not free of counterveiling
risks....the possibility that these compounds could cause long-term,
chronic effects, including cancer, is now a subject of intensive
research by toxicologists and epidemiologists.&quot;<BR>

<P>
Balancing these risks is not a trivial matter. In Peru, a decision
to reduce the chlorination of public drinking water may have been
responsible for an outbreak of cholera that killed thousands of
people.<BR>

<P>
This problem of trade-offs - and how to get the biggest bang for
the environmental buck - lay at the heart of 1995 Congressional
proposals to institute cost-benefit analysis and risk assessment.
Reform proposals need to incorporate &quot;balancing mechanisms&quot;
- decision processes that foster a balancing of costs against
benefits and establish means for setting priorities. But balancing
may be better achieved through bargaining processes than through
top-down rules that impose detailed analytical requirements on
regulators. <BR>

<P>
<I>Principle of Accountability and Stewardship</I>. Economists
Richard Stroup and John Baden conclude that institutions, not
perverse people, are the genesis of environmental problems. Policies
that more closely link the choices that individuals make with
outcomes for those choices strengthen incentives for stewardship
and efficiency. Paying to use resources, for example, establishes
incentives to conserve the same resources.<BR>

<P>
But this linkage applies to public decisions as well. Current
policies that require individuals or firms to set aside land for
wildlife, wilderness and wetlands protection in effect ask these
people to provide a public amenity at no cost to the public. Compensating
private individuals (or firms) in those instances in which they
are asked to provide a public amenity is not merely a matter of
fairness. It also gives property owners a financial self-interest
in protecting habitat and preserving endangered species. And it
gives regulators an incentive to prioritize their efforts.<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><a name="do"></a><B>What Can Policymakers Do</B>?<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
An environmental vision must precede policy reform because it
shapes the principles of progress. It provides a basis for developing
principles against which to construct and evaluate different policy
reform tools. It establishes some notion of what reformers value,
and it offers, as Walter Lippman wrote in his 1965 book, <B>Public
Opinion</B>, a &quot;map of the universe&quot; - a sense of the
nature of knowledge and how people create and tap into relevant
knowledge to make decisions.<BR>

<P>
But a vision, and the principles that flow from that vision, are
necessarily abstract. Policy reformers, however, must deal in
specifics. What might an agenda for reform look like?<BR>

<P>
Former EPA chief William Ruckelshaus correctly concluded in his
fall 1995 speech at the Environmental Law Institute's annual awards
dinner in Washington, D.C. that, &quot;despite the current rhetoric
in this city, there is no simple fix, no silver bullet.&quot;
Aligning environmental policies with a new vision that highlights
problem-solving rather than punishment, dynamic use of decentralized
information, and a balancing among many values will require an
overhaul of many current statutes. And it will need to be an evolutionary
process. Three kinds of statutes might start that process.<BR>

<P>
<I>Environmental Devolution Statute</I>. The first step would
include passage of a general statute to devolve responsibilities
and authority for many environmental programs to states. Several
ideas for such a statute have been outlined by the Washington,
D.C.-based National Environmental Policy Institute and other groups.
These ideas serve as a useful starting point. An Environmental
Devolution Statute, focused on most air, water and hazardous waste
regulations, should:<BR>

<UL>
<LI>Devolve to the states authority, responsibility and accountability
for setting environmental goals, implementing policy and monitoring
success. Where airsheds or watersheds cross state boundaries,
states would have primary authority for working out acceptable
standards, and the national role would be one of mediator. 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Create sunset provisions to phase out existing legislation
<I>as revised environmental laws</I> are introduced. 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Create a performance-based system in which the emphasis is
on setting ambient environmental standards, not on the use of
specific technologies. 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Establish mechanisms for development of multi-media, facility-wide,
or even community-wide, ambient standards and permitting that
would allow for emission trading among facilities, among different
emission sources within a single plant and even possibly among
different pollution sources. Permits could take the form of contracts
or covenants rather than the more traditional regulatory permits.

</UL>

<P>
The primary purpose of such a statute would be to create procedures
for decentralizing decision-making and developing flexible conditions
in which success is measured by real-world accomplishments, not
by prospective EPA approvals based on modeled predictions of how
EPA thinks different technologies and programs might affect environmental
quality.<BR>

<P>
<I>Civic Environmentalism Act</I>. The second step for environmental
reform would include a Civic Environmentalism Act passed by Congress.
Designed to shift emphasis away from primarily punitive approaches
to policies that promote problem-solving, bargaining and technical
information and information exchange, this act would:<BR>

<UL>
<LI>Reform environmental enforcement by clarifying which actions
are subject to criminal penalties and which are subject to civil
and administrative proceedings; tie criminal penalties primarily
to situations in which intent to harm is present; revise sentencing
guidelines so that environmental sentences conform more closely
with guidelines for other, comparable crimes; and, limit dual
prosecutions for the same violation by different agencies. 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Create an environmental extension program patterned after
agricultural extension programs in which information and technical
assistance are provided to farmers and businesses to achieve emission
reductions as a substitute for enforcement actions in situations
where neither &quot;intent to harm&quot; nor &quot;gross negligence&quot;
exists. Such programs need not require new expenditures but could
involve a shifting of current expenditures away from punitive
approaches, or they could use proceeds from pollution charges,
or such programs could use private funding. 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Facilitate the establishment of local, market-like bargaining
and negotiating processes through which those directly affected
by particular pollution and other environmental harms can negotiate
with the individuals, firms or governments responsible for those
harms concerning appropriate clean-up levels and ambient standards.
Models for these programs already exist within some states, for
some kinds of projects. 
</UL>

<P>
A Civic Environmentalism Act would represent a major departure
from the regulatory approaches established over the past thirty
years. The goal of such an act would be to begin the process of
&quot;privatizing&quot; decision-making regarding some environmental
problems, and creating bargaining approaches for problems such
as Superfund site clean-ups, brownfields redevelopment, Federal
facilities clean-ups, toxic emission standard-setting and other
problems with primarily local impacts.<BR>

<P>
<I>Environmental Amenities Act</I>. The third step in environmental
reform would be an Environmental Amenities Act patterned in part
after the 1995 House proposals for takings compensation to property
owners who lose some (or all) use of their property to provide
public environmental amenities such as wilderness, wildlife and
wetlands protection. The overall purpose of an Environmental Amenities
Act would be to replace the regulatory and punitive approaches
of the current Endangered Species Act and wetlands regulations
developed under the Clean Water Act with market approaches that
create incentives for environmental stewardship and relieve individual
property owners or firms from shouldering the burdens of providing
public amenities at private rather than taxpayer expense. An Environmental
Amenities Act would:<BR>

<UL>
<LI>Create requirements for takings compensation in situations
where private landowners are required to provide public amenities;
such provisions <I>do not</I> include compensation against regulations
regarding pollution reduction or mitigation. 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Empower states to &quot;privatize&quot; benefits of wildlife
and habitat protection by encouraging use of bounties, competitive
contracts for private entities to provide habitat and wildlife
protection, and other measures that allow private individuals,
firms, ranchers and forest owners to &quot;capture value&quot;
by producing environmental goods. 
</UL>

<P>
The purpose of an Environmental Amenities Act would be to strengthen
accountability - both in the private and public sectors.<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><a name="better"></a><B>A Better Future<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
All environmental decisions involve a tug-of-war among competing
values. This includes a tug-of-war among substantive values -
my sphere of values versus my neighbor's and one value versus
another.<BR>

<P>
The tug-of-war also includes juggling among what I call decision-process
values. All decision-making processes experience, to varying degrees
along a continuum, a tension between predictability and flexibility;
uniformity and diversity; certainty and dynamism; anticipation
of all harms and resilience - the ability to respond effectively
when problems arise.<BR>

<P>
For thirty years, however, legislators have opted for environmental
policies that have emphasized predictability, centralization,
certainty and uniformity. These decision characteristics are ill-suited
to a dynamic world in which people hold diverse values and problems
are complex and often location-specific. Such a world requires
decision processes that enhance autonomy, personal stewardship,
flexibility, decentralization, adaptation and resilience. 
<br>
<br>
<center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center><br>
</blockquote>
</BODY>
</HTML>
