          unnecessary loopholes in the tax code.
</blockquote><p>
McIntyre, Robert S. 1995a. "The Flat Taxers' Flat Deceptions." <i>The American Prospect</i> (Summer), pp. 93-95.
<p>
McIntyre, Robert S. 1995b.  "Are the Rich Really Overtaxed?" <i>Washington Post</i> (July 20).
<p>
McKenzie, Richard. 1982.  "A Case Against the Flat-Rate Tax."  <i>Washington Times</i> (October 20).
<blockquote>
          A professor of economics at Clemson believes that
          elimination of tax deductions, even if rates are
          lowered, would ultimately lead to higher taxes. 
          Believes that a narrow tax base prevents government
          from raising taxes as much as it would like.  See also
          McCaleb (1985).
</blockquote><p>
Merrill, Peter, Ken Wertz, and Shvetank Shah. 1995.  "Corporate Tax Liability Under the USA and Flat Taxes."  <i>Tax Notes</i>,
     vol. 68, no. 6 (August 7), pp. 741-745.
<p>
Miller, Glenn H., Jr. 1984.  "Alternatives to the Current
     Individual Income Tax."  <i>Economic Review</i>, Federal Reserve
     Bank of Kansas City (September/October): 3-16.
<P>
Minarik, Joseph J. 1985.  "Semantics of the Flat Rate Tax and Tax
     Reform."  <i>Cato Journal</i>, vol. 5, no. 2 (Fall), pp. 437-448.
<blockquote>
          Raises concerns about whether a flat-rate tax would
          constitute genuine tax reform.
</blockquote><p>
Mitchell, Daniel J. 1995a.  "A Brief Guide to the Flat Tax."  <i>Talking Points</i>, The Heritage Foundation (March 22).
<p>
Mitchell, Daniel J. 1995b.  "Jobs, Growth, Freedom, and Fairness:
     Why America Needs a Flat Tax." <i>Backgrounder</i> No. 1035, The
     Heritage Foundation (May 25).
<p>
Mufson, Steven. 1992.  "Analysts Question the Depth of Brown's Flat Tax Proposal."  <i>Washington Post</i> (March 28).
<blockquote>
          Reviews Brown proposal.
</blockquote><p>
Neikirk, Bill. 1981.  "Has Time Come for Flat Tax Rate?"  <i>Chicago Tribune</i> (August 10).
<p>
New York Times. 1992.  "Mr. Brown's Flat Tax: Tilted."  <i>New York
     Times</i> (March 27).
<blockquote>
                    Opposes Jerry Brown's changes to Hall-Rabushka
          proposal.
</blockquote><p>
Nordhaus, William. 1982.  "A Proposed Flat Tax for Fat Cats."  <i>New York Times</i> (November 28).
<blockquote>
          A professor of economics at Yale strongly opposes a
          flat-rate tax on normative grounds.
</blockquote><p>
Office of Federal Tax Services. 1982.  "Flat-Rate Tax: An
     Overview and Comparison of Proposals and Reflections on
     Transitional Issues."  <i>Washington Tax Letter</i>, Arthur
     Andersen & Co. (August 6).
<blockquote>
          Takes no position for or against a flat-rate tax, but
          calls attention to important transitional issues in
          moving from current tax system to a flat-rate system.
</blockquote><p>
O'Kelley, Charles R., Jr. 1985.  "Tax Policy for Post-Liberal Society: A Flat-Rate-Inspired Redefinition of the Purpose
     and Ideal Structure of a Progressive Income Tax."  <i>Southern
     California Law Review</i>, vol. 58, no. 3 (March), pp. 727-776.
<blockquote>
          Favors a flat-rate on incomes above the minimum wage.
</blockquote><p>
O'Neill, Harry, and Kenneth Schwartz. 1982.  "Flat Tax Facts."  <i>Public Opinion</i> (October/November), pp. 44-46.
<blockquote>
          Reports on a public opinion survey on flat rate tax. 
          Indicates that 45% favor flat-rate, 41% favor
          progressive tax.  However, 20% to 30% of flat-rate
          supporters would reject it if forced to give-up
          particular deductions.
</blockquote><p>
<a name="P"></a>P-R<p>
<a href="#quick">Back to QuickLinks</a><p>

Paul, Ron. 1982.  "The Flatter the Better?"  <i>Inquiry</i> (September),
     pp. 29-33.
<blockquote>
          Prominent libertarian (he was the Libertarian Party's
          presidential candidate in 1984) strongly favors a flat-
rate tax because "it would spread the burden of paying
          for government more evenly, foreclosing once and for
          all the illusion that the burden can be placed on the
          shoulders of the rich.  By shifting the tax burden
          toward the political center, any flat-rate tax would
          increase pressure for less government taxing and
          spending."  Contrast with Rothbard.
</blockquote><p>
Payne, James L. 1993.  <i>Costly Returns: The Burdens of the U.S. Tax System</i>.  San Francisco: ICS Press.
<blockquote>
          Estimates the compliance cost of the federal tax system
          at 65% of revenue collected.  Contrast with Blumenthal
          and Slemrod (1992) and Slemrod and Sorum (1984).
</blockquote><p>
Pechman, Joseph A., and Michael J. Boskin. 1982.  "Flat Rate Taxes: Two Views."  <i>Tax Notes</i> (August 16), pp. 651-653.
<blockquote>
          A tax expert from the Brookings Institution and a
          professor of economics at Stanford debate the
          desirability of a flat-rate tax.  Pechman is against it
          and Boskin is for it.
</blockquote><p>
Pechman, Joseph A., and John Karl Scholz. 1982.  "Comprehensive Income Taxation and Rate Reduction."  <i>Tax Notes</i> (October
     11), pp. 83-93.
<p>
Penner, Rudolph G. 1982.  "The More or Less Flat Tax."  <i>The AEI Economist</i> (August).
<blockquote>
          Generally favorable to flat-rate tax on a consumption
          base.
</blockquote><p>
Pollock, Sheldon. 1995. "Flatliners." <i>The New Republic</i> (September
     18 & 25), pp. 18-22.
<p>
Prakken, Joel L., Laurence H. Meyer, and Chris P. Vavares. 1984. 
     <i>Flat Taxes and Capital Formation</i>.  St. Louis: Washington
     University, Center for the Study of American Business.
<blockquote>
          Analyzes Kemp-Kasten and Bradley-Gephardt proposals
          with an econometric model.  Finds that both would
          reduce investment and economic growth.
</blockquote><p>
Prowse, Michael. 1995. "The Magical Allure of Flat Taxes."
    <i>Financial Times</i> (July 17).
<p>
Prowse, Michael. 1996.  "Flat Tax Frenzy."  <i>Financial Times</i> (January 22).
<P>
Quayle, Dan. 1982.  "Making Taxes Simpler."  <i>Washington Post</i> (June 7), p. A15.
<blockquote>
          A U.S. Senator from Indiana favors a two-rate tax
          system (18% and 25%).
</blockquote><p>
Raboy, David. 1982.  "The Flat-Rate Tax--An Introduction to the Issues."  <i>Economic Report No. 12</i>, Institute for Research on
     the Economics of Taxation (December 17).
<blockquote>
          Favors flat-rate tax, but believes that the really
          important issue is the tax base (i.e., what is taxed).
</blockquote><p>
Rabushka, Alvin. 1979.  <i>Hong Kong: A Study In Economic Freedom</i>. 
     Chicago: University of Chicago, Graduate School of Business.
<blockquote>
                    Reviews experience of Hong Kong with flat-rate tax
          system.  See also Chow and Papanek (1981) and Byrne
          (1982).
</blockquote><p>
Rabushka, Alvin. 1981.  "The Attractions of a Flat-Rate Tax System."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (March 25).
<p>
Rabushka, Alvin. 1996.  "Flat Tax Lite."  <i>New York Times</i> (January
     23).
<p>
Reed, Ralph. 1982.  <i>The Flat Rate Income Tax</i>.  Washington:
     Washington Research Foundation.
<blockquote>
          The author, now head of the Christian Coalition,
          strongly supports a flat-rate tax system.
</blockquote><p>
Reynolds, Alan. 1992.  "Flat Chance: Jerry Brown's Only Good Idea."  <i>The New Republic</i> (April 20), pp. 14-16.
<blockquote>
          Supports Brown proposal of a flat 13% rate on
          individuals plus a 13% VAT.  Is especially supportive
          of Brown plan's elimination of Social Security tax as
          part of his proposal.
</blockquote><p>
Richman, Louis S. 1995.  "The Flat Tax."  <i>Fortune</i> (June 12), pp.
     36-46.
<p>
Robbins, Gary, and Aldona Robbins. 1992.  "Jerry Brown's Tax Plan."  <i>Policy Backgrounder</i> No. 117, National Center for
     Policy Analysis (April 16).
<blockquote>
          Two former Treasury Department economists evaluate the
          flat-rate tax proposal put forward by former California
          Governor Jerry Brown (a 13% flat rate on individuals
          plus a 13% VAT on businesses).  They find large
          efficiency gains.
</blockquote><p>
Roberts, Paul Craig. 1982.  "How to Break the Stalemate Over the
     Budget."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (May 3).
<blockquote>
          Raises concern that Reagan Administration support for
          higher taxes through base-broadening (i.e, Tax Equity
          and Fiscal Responsibility Act) without corresponding
          rate reduction will erode support for administration.
</blockquote><p>
Rosenbaum, David E. 1995.  "Debate on Flat Tax Revives Simplicity
     vs. Fairness Issue."  <i>New York Times</i> (April 18).
<p>
Rothbard, Murray. 1982a.  "Flat-Rate: The Latest Con." <i>The Libertarian Forum</i> (July), p. 2.
<blockquote>
          Believes that a major motive for flat-rate is envy--
forcing everyone to "pay their fair share."
</blockquote><p>
Rothbard, Murray. 1982b.  "The Flat Rate Trap."  <i>Libertarian Vanguard</i> (August), pp. 1-4.
<blockquote>
          Opposes flat-rate tax because it would eliminate
          deductions which presently protect taxpayers from
          taxation.
</blockquote><p>
Rothbard, Murray. 1982c.  "Flat-Rate Debate."  <i>Reason</i>
     (September), p. 47.
<blockquote>
          Believes that middle class would pay more taxes under
          flat-rate system.
</blockquote><p>
Rothbard, Murray. 1985.  "The Flat Tax: A Skeptical View."  <i>Issues in Economic Policy</i>, Ludwig von Mises Institute.
<blockquote>
          Believes that a flat-rate tax would be neither fairer
          nor more economically sound than existing tax system.
</blockquote><p>
Rowan, Carl T. 1982.  "Don't Buy That Flat-Rate Tax."
     <i>Washington Post</i> (June 25).
<blockquote>
          Strongly opposes a flat-rate tax.
</blockquote><p>
Ruby, Michael. 1995.  "Three Cheers for a Flat Tax!"  <i>U.S. News &
     World Report</i> (February 20), p. 76.
<p>
Rudnick, Rebecca S. 1989.  "Who Should Pay the Corporate Tax in a
     Flat Tax World?"  <i>Case Western Reserve Law Review</i>, vol. 39,
     no. 4, pp. 965-1269.
<p>
<a name="S"></a>S-V<p>
<a href="#quick">Back to QuickLinks</a><p>

Safire, William. 1982.  "The Flat Tax."  <i>New York Times</i> (April 30).
<blockquote>
          Favors flat-rate because existing web of exemptions
          encourages tax evasion; because it would save billions
          now spent on lawyers and accountants to explain tax
          law; and because tax law should not be used to affect
          social policy.
</blockquote><p>
Samuelson, Robert J. 1982.  "Installing Flat Tax Would Prove Messy."  <i>Washington Post</i> (May 18).
<blockquote>
          Favors retention of progressivity because rich receive
          more benefits from government.
</blockquote><p>
Samuelson, Robert J. 1996.  "Call It the Flaky Tax."  <i>Newsweek</i> (January 29), p. 27.
<p>
Schaefer, Rebecca S. 1995.  "Straight Talk About the Flat Tax." 
     Issues and Answers, <i>Citizens for a Sound Economy</i> (May 4).
<p>
Schoeck, Helmut. 1966.  <i>Envy: A Theory of Social Behavior</i>.  New York: Harcourt, Brace & World, pp. 323-330.
<blockquote>
          Discusses progressive taxation as an aspect of envy--
the desire to punish others for their success.
</blockquote><p>
Senate Finance Committee. 1982.  <i>Flat-Rate Tax</i>.  2 parts, 97th Congress, 2nd session.  Washington: U.S. Government Printing
     Office.
<blockquote>
          Most extensive hearings ever held on flat-rate tax. 
          Contains testimony from the U.S. Treasury Department,
          many senators, experts of various kinds, as well as a
          wide number of special interest groups.
</blockquote><p>
Senate Finance Committee. 1995.  <i>Flat Tax Proposals</i>.  Senate Hearing 104-209, 104th Congress, 1st session.  Washington:
     U.S. Government Printing Office.
<blockquote>
          Contains testimony by Alan Auerbach, UC-Berkely; Joel
          Slemrod, University of Michigan; Bruce Bartlett, NCPA;
          Michael Graetz, Yale; Laurence Kotlikoff, Boston
          University; and Alvin Rabushka, Hoover Institution.
</blockquote><p>
Shelton, Judy. 1995. "A Flat Tax for a Strong Dollar." <i>Washington
     Post</i> (September 6).
<blockquote>
          Believes that a flat tax would strengthen the dollar. 
          For a contrary view, see Dunn (1995).
</blockquote><p>
Shlaes, Amity. 1995. "Flat Tax Flap."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i>
     (October 20)
<p>
Simon, William E. 1982.  "What a Flat-Rate Income Tax Would Mean
     to You."  <i>Reader's Digest</i> (November), pp. 122-126.
<blockquote>
          A former Secretary of the Treasury strongly favors a
          flat-rate tax because it would be fairer and because it
          would stimulate economic growth.
</blockquote><p>
Simon, William E. 1995.  "Flat Tax Is Test of GOP's Sincerity." 
    <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (May 24).
<p>
Slemrod, Joel, and Nikki Sorum. 1984.  "The Compliance Cost of the U.S. Individual Income Tax System." <i>National Tax
     Journal</i>, vol. 37, no. 4 (December), pp. 461-474.
<blockquote>
          Estimates the compliance cost of the federal and state
          individual income tax systems at between $17 and $27
          billion in 1982, or 5% to 7% of revenue collected.  See
          also Payne (1993) and Blumental and Slemrod (1992).
</blockquote><p>
Slemrod, Joel, and Shlomo Yitzhaki. 1983.  "On Choosing a Flat-Rate Income Tax System."  <i>National Tax Journal</i>, vol. 36, no.
     1 (March), pp. 31-44.
<blockquote>
          Presents data allowing flat-rate advocates to choose
          among various tax rate and tax base assumptions.
</blockquote><p>
Smith, Dan Throop. 1968.  "High Progressive Tax Rates: Inequality
     and Immorality."  <i>University of Florida Law Review</i>, vol. 20,
     no. 4 (Spring), pp. 451-463.
<blockquote>
          A professor of finance at the Harvard Business School
          argues against high progressive tax rates principally
          on the grounds that they encourage tax evasion and
          undermine compliance with the tax law.
</blockquote><p>
Stokey, Nancy L., and Sergio Rebelo. 1995.  "Growth Effects of Flat-Rate Taxes."  <i>Journal of Political Economy</i>, vol. 103,
     no. 3 (June), pp. 519-550.
<blockquote>
          Finds modest growth effects from tax reform.
</blockquote><p>
Stuart, Charles. 1984.  "Welfare Costs per Dollar of Additional Tax Revenue in the United States."  <i>American Economic
     Review</i>, vol. 74, no. 3 (June), pp. 352-62.
<blockquote>
          Finds that the marginal welfare cost per tax dollar may
          be as high as $1.
</blockquote><p>
Sullivan, Martin. 1995.  <i>Flat Taxes and Consumption Taxes: A Guide to the Debate</i>.  Washington: American Institute of
     Certified Public Accountants.
<p>
Talley, Louis Alan. 1982.  "Estimates of Flat Income Tax Rates Using Various Tax Bases."  <i>Tax Notes </i>(June 21), pp. 952-956.
<blockquote>
          An economist at the Congressional Research Service
          points out that economic effects of flat-rate tax
          depend critically on definition of taxable income
          (i.e., tax base).
</blockquote><p>
Tannenwald, Robert. 1983.  "Redistribution of Wealth in
     Conversion to a Flat Rate Tax."  <i>New England Economic
     Review</i>, Federal Reserve Bank of Boston (January/February),
     pp. 5-17.
<blockquote>
          Because taxes and tax preferences are capitalized in
          the value of assets, any move toward a flat-rate tax
          will have wealth effects.  Finds that middle income
          investors will bear heaviest burden of transition.
</blockquote><p>
Taylor, Robert C. 1986.  "Low Marginal Rates Could Backfire."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (June 10).
<blockquote>
          Opposes tax reform and believes that many deductions
          serve a useful social purpose.
</blockquote><p>
Tax Foundation. 1985.  <i>Flatter Taxes and Fatter Bases</i>. 
     Washington: Tax Foundation.
<p>
Ture, Norman. 1982.  "The Flat Tax Challenge."  <i>Backgrounder</i> No.
     212, The Heritage Foundation (September 21).
<blockquote>
          A former under secretary of the Treasury argues that
          rate structure of the income tax is less important than
          the overall impact of the tax system.  Favors greater
          tax neutrality
</blockquote><p>
Ture, Norman. 1994.  "The Flat Tax: A Guide to Constructive Tax Restructuring." <i> Commonsense</i> (Fall), pp. 35-47.
<p>
U.S. Treasury Department. 1984.  <i>Tax Reform for Fairness,
     Simplicity, and Economic Growth: The Treasury Department
     Report to the President</i>, vol. 1, Overview.  Washington: U.S.
     Government Printing Office (November), pp. 21-23.
<blockquote>
          Argues against a pure flat-rate tax on distributional
          grounds.
</blockquote><p>
U.S. Treasury Department. 1986.  <i>Report to Congress on an
     Economic Analysis of Gross Income Taxes</i>.  Washington:
     Department of the Treasury, Office of the Secretary, Office
     of Tax Analysis (November).
<blockquote>
          Opposes a flat tax proposal known as a gross receipts
          tax because it would allow no deduction for business
          expenses, thus resulting in "cascading" and sharp
          variations in tax rates from one business to another. 
          See also U.S. General Accounting Office (1989).
</blockquote><p>
U.S. Treasury Department. 1992.  <i>Restructuring the U.S. Tax System for the 21st Century: An Option for Fundamental
     Reform</i>.  Washington: U.S. Treasury Department.
<p>
U.S. Treasury Department. 1995. <i>An Analysis of the New Armey-Shelby Flat Tax Proposal</i>.  Washington: U.S. Treasury
     Department, Office of Tax Analysis.
<blockquote>
          Revenue and distributional analysis of one flat tax
          proposal.  Finds that it would be revenue-neutral at a
          20.8% rate.  This report was also published in Tax
          Notes, vol. 70, no. 4 (January 22, 1996), pp. 451-61.
</blockquote><p>
Vedder, Richard K. 1986.  "Tithing for Leviathan: The Case for a
     True Flat-Rate Tax."  In Dwight Lee, ed., <i>Taxation and the
     Deficit Economy: Fiscal Policy and Capital Formation in the
     United States</i>.  San Francisco: Pacific Institute for Public
     Policy, pp. 141-169.
<blockquote>
          A professor of economics at Ohio University favors a
          pure flat-rate tax system.
</blockquote><p>
Vedder, Richard, and Christopher Frenze. 1983.  "Fairness and the
     Flat Rate Tax."  <i>Journal of Contemporary Studies</i>, vol. 6,
     no. 1 (Winter), pp. 45-50.
<blockquote>
          Indicate that Hall-Rabushka proposal would restore the
          tax system to roughly the same level of progressivity
          prevailing when John F. Kennedy was president.
</blockquote><p>
<a name="W"></a>W-Z<p>
<a href="#quick">Back to QuickLinks</a><p>
Washington Post. 1982a.  "Tax Day."  <i>Washington Post</i> (April 15).
<blockquote>
          Editorial favors flat tax.  For criticism, see Manvel
          (1982).
</blockquote><p>
Washington Post. 1982b.  "Flat-Out Taxes."  <i>Washington Post</i> (June
     3).
<p>
Wattenberg, Daniel. 1992.  "Supply-side Brownnoser or Savior?"  <i>Insight</i> (April 5), pp. 12-13, 30.
<blockquote>
          Reviews proposal by former California Governor Jerry
          Brown.  Cites support for proposal by supply-side
          economists Arthur Laffer and Jude Wanniski.
</blockquote><p>
Wessel, David. 1995. "Talk of Tax Reform Is Gaining Momentum, But
     Plans Vary Widely." <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (January 31).
<p>
Wildavsky, Rachel. 1996.  "How Fair Are Our Taxes?" <i>Reader's Digest</i> (February), pp. 57-61.
<blockquote>
          Reports a survey indicating that most Americans think a
          family earning $200,000 should not pay more than 25% in
          taxes.  In fact, these families already pay 39%.
</blockquote><p>
Wildstrom, Stephen H. 1982.  "The Flat-Rate Tax: An Old Idea With
     New Appeal."  <i>Business Week</i> (July 19), pp. 130-131.
<blockquote>
          Believes that discussion of flat-rate tax has been
          helpful in drawing attention to the relationship
          between tax rates and the tax base.
</blockquote><p>
Will, George F. 1992.  "Brown's Burlesque."  <i>Washington Post</i> (April 9).
<blockquote>
                    A prominent conservative columnist supports Brown
          proposal and attacks progressivity.
</blockquote><p>
Yin, George K. 1995.  "Accomodating the 'Low-Income' in a Cash-Flow or Consumed Income Tax World."  <i>Florida Tax Review</i>,
     vol. 2, no. 8, pp. 445-491.
<blockquote>
          Finds that the EITC is not feasible under a
          consumption-based tax system.  Therefore, such a tax
          system cannot be as beneficial to the poor as the
          current tax system.
</blockquote><p>
Yoder, Edwin M., Jr. 1982.  "The Fever Over the Flat Tax."  <i>Washington Post</i> (July 14).
<blockquote>
          Sees nothing wrong with tax loopholes and therefore
          little to be gained from flat-rate. 
</blockquote><p>
<p>
