<html>
<title>Careers Act</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<p>
<center><h2>CAREERS: Nothing to Strive For</h2></center>
<p>
<p>
<hr>
 <p> 		             

A growing number of state legislators are voicing their opposition to <a href="http://www.house.gov/eeo/status_bills.html">H.R. 1617</a>, known as the <b>CAREERS</b> bill, which would expand and make permanent the School-to-Work Act passed by Congress in 1994. <p>

In a letter to House Speaker Newt Gingrich and the Missouri Republican delegation, 
Missouri legislators said that <a href="http://www.house.gov/eeo/status_bills.html">H.R. 1617</a> "incorporates word-for-word many sections of Goals 2000, include the <b>removal of local control from education</b> and the <b>centralization of power to the federal government</b> including the need for approval from the Department of <a href="http://www.dol.gov">Labor</a> and <a href="http://www.ed.gov/">Education</a> for a state's proposal to grant money. <p>

"The terms used in the acts are of concern as they refer to items such as a 'skills certificate' which children would be required to earn and which employers would be encouraged to require as a condition of employment.<p>

"Finally, a myraid of new agencies, department, and programs are created...and it appears that a <b>large, centralized, nationwide data collection system</b> will be put in place." <p>

<a href="/townhall/FRC/">The Family Research Council</a> has also expressed concern on behalf of thousands of families across the country. <p>

In a recent <i>Alert</i>, Family Research Council elaborated on the provisions it found unacceptable:
<ul>
<li><b>The inclusion of youth in a seamless system of workforce development</b>.  
The needs of youth are much different from those of an unemployed adult.  Vocational education should be a matter left to the local control of elected boards, not merged into a complex new workforce development infrastructure.
<p>
<li><b>The creation of a workforce development infrastructure</b>.  The CAREERS bill requires the creation of state and local workforce development baords that will oversee all aspects of the "seamless system" of workforce development.  These boards will be appointed, <i>not</i> elected.  
<p>
<li><b>The Labor Market Information System (LMIS)</b>. This system has the potential to collect data on every American employer, worker and student.  Proponents of the bill rationalize LMIS by claiming the need for jobseekers to be able to access information on job openings across the country.  Why should the government duplicate information already provided by trade associations, business journals, and classified ads everywhere?
<p>
<br>
<center><b>How To Act</b>:<br><br>
Eagle Forum Alert: <a href="http://www.basenet.net/~eagle/alert/careers.html">Are You Opposed to CAREERS?</a><p>
<br>
<b>Other Resources and Links</b>:<p>
<a href="http://www.basenet.net/~eagle/alert/careers2.html">A Summary Critique of CAREERS</a><br>
<a href="/townhall/FRC/infocus/if95i1ed.html">Careers: A Missed Opportunity</a><br>
<a href="/townhall/FRC/infocus/if95k8ed.html">What is Goals 2000?</a><br>
<a href="/townhall/FRC/insight/is95c1ed.html">Goals 2000: The Case for Repeal</a><br>
<p>
<p>
<A HREF="/townhall/tbut.map">
<IMG SRC="/townhall/tbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>

</center>
</body>
</html> 
					
					






</DOC>
