<TITLE>WHO ARE THE "EXTREMISTS"?</TITLE>
<BODY>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<P>
<H2>WHO ARE THE "EXTREMISTS"?<BR>
</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 50%>
<P>
<CENTER>
<I>by</I>
<P>
<I> Gracie S. Hsu</I></CENTER>
<P>
In response to mounting problems, the White House has adopted
a new strategy to promote the nomination of Dr. Henry Foster as
Surgeon General.  It has chosen to frame the debate as a referendum
on the legality of abortion and to label its opponents as right-to-life
&quot;extremists.&quot; 
<P>
The White House's attempt to evoke a knee-jerk reaction from the
American public fails to address the salient issues of the debate,
however.  The Foster nomination is <U>not</U> about the legality
of abortion, and those calling for Foster's withdrawal are not
&quot;extreme.&quot;
<P>
The dictionary defines &quot;extremism&quot; as deviating to the
greatest degree from the center of opinion.  So what is the center
of opinion?  On the issue of abortion, the White House implicitly
argues that Henry Foster represents the center of public opinion.
 However, public opinion polls compiled by the American Enterprise
Institute show that Henry Foster occupies one end of the abortion
spectrum and that the majority of Americans do <U>not</U> subscribe
to Dr. Foster's views.
<UL>
<LI> A 1994 Gallup poll commissioned by CNN and <I>USA Today</I>
found that 65 percent of Americans believe that abortions should
either be &quot;illegal in all circumstances&quot; or &quot;legal
under certain circumstances.&quot;  Only 33 percent would agree
with Dr. Foster that abortions should be &quot;legal under any
circumstances.&quot;
<P>
<LI> A 1995 CBS News/<I>New York Times</I> poll (1/95) found that
60 percent believe that abortion should either &quot;not be permitted&quot;
or have &quot;stricter limits.&quot;  Dr. Foster's views that
abortion should be &quot;generally available&quot; are shared
by only 38 percent of the population.
<P>
<LI>A 1994 Roper study commissioned by Focus on the Family and the
Family Research Council polled abortion views on a 9-point continuum.
 From category 1 representing the most pro-life stance to category
9 representing the most pro-abortion stance, Dr. Foster's views
place him in either category 8 or 9.  Only 13 percent of Americans
fall into those two categories combined.
</UL>
<P>
Dr. Foster's record shows that he vigorously opposes popular measures
such as waiting periods and parental consent and notification
laws.  Foster also believes that abortions should be available
through all nine months of pregnancy, even 
after the fetus is viable outside of the mother's womb.  Can Dr.
Foster, as an 
individual who not only holds these views, but has also personally
performed abortions, conducted studies on mothers and their unborn
children to test abortion drugs, and performed sterilizations
on mentally retarded young women without their consent, be accurately
described as holding to the center of this public opinion?
<P>
And then there's the issue of Dr. Foster's credibility.  Dr. Foster
and the White House have not been forthright in representing Foster's
abortion record.  First, the White House said nothing about abortion.
 Then it admitted to Sen. Nancy Kassebaum that Foster had performed
<B>one</B> abortion.  Then Dr. Foster issued a statement saying
that he had done &quot;<B>fewer than a dozen</B>.&quot;  Then
there was the 1978 Department of Health, Education, and Welfare
transcript that recorded Foster as saying he had done &quot;<B>probably
near 700</B>&quot; amniocentesis tests and therapeutic abortions.
 Then Dr. Foster admitted his involvement in <B>55</B> abortions
when conducting abortion drug trials in 1981.  Then Foster told
<I>Nightline</I> that he was the &quot;physician of record&quot;
for <B>39</B> abortions.
<P>
The issue of credibility is hardly a minor point, especially for
an individual in whom Americans are asked to repose their trust.
 Are Foster's critics &quot;extreme&quot; for wanting a Surgeon
General who is truthful and forthright?
<P>
Lastly, the White House has characterized Foster's critics as
&quot;right to life extremists.&quot;  As of this writing, those
calling for the withdrawal of the Foster nomination include pro-life
groups, pro-family groups, the New York chapter of the National
Organization for Women, the <I>New York Times</I>, the <I>Washington
Post</I>, the <I>Washington Times</I>, the National Coalition
of Abortion Providers, Senators Joseph Biden, Nancy Kassebaum,
Bob Dole, and Dan Coats, among others.  Are all of these &quot;right
to life extremists&quot;?  If so, then where does that put the
White House and Henry Foster?  If not, then why has the White
House singled out the pro-life community for its rhetorical venom?
<P>
Groups coming from many different perspectives oppose the Foster
nomination for many different reasons.  Yet the White House has
chosen to label anyone who doesn't agree with its position as
&quot;extreme&quot;?  Did I miss something, or does the White
House now hold a monopoly on what can be considered &quot;mainstream&quot;?
<P>
 <CENTER>***</CENTER>
<P>
<I>Gracie S. Hsu, M.H.S., is a policy analyst specializing in
human sexuality and life issues at the Family Research Council,
a Washington, D.C.-based research and advocacy organization.</I>

