<html>

<title>MANY COUPLES STILL WAITING TO ADOPT CHILDREN</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">

<p>
<h2>MANY COUPLES STILL WAITING<br>
TO ADOPT CHILDREN</h2></center>
<hr size = 3 width = 50%>
<p>

The National Council for Adoption (NCFA) conservatively estimates
that there are at least one million infertile and fertile couples
who are waiting to adopt children.[1] For every one adoptable infant
available, there are at least 40 couples hoping to adopt.[2] Today,
it is not unusual to pick up a local newspaper and find an advertisement
placed by a married couple searching for a child to adopt.
<p>
What is causing this high &quot;adoption demand&quot;? While the
answer is no doubt multi-faceted and complex, the following factors
have contributed to this phenomenon:
<p><ul>
<li><b>Plummeting adoption rates among unwed mothers --</b> Despite
the four-fold increase in the number of births to unmarried women
since 1967, the number of these unwed mothers choosing to place
their children for adoption declined by one-third during that
same time period.[3] Thus, while about one in five premarital births
to white women was placed for adoption in the late 1960s, by 1988,
this proportion had shrunk to one in 30.[4]
<p>
<li><b>Abortion</b> -- Approximately 1.5 million abortions take
place in the United States every year. About one-quarter of these
abortions are to teenagers, and more than four-fifths are to unmarried
mothers.[5] Each of these aborted pregnancies represents a potential
adoption; and if adoption rather than abortion were chosen in
these instances, the high adoption demand could be greatly alleviated.
<p>
<li><b>Infertility</b> -- The demand for adoptable babies remains
high due to continued infertility. Two sources of infertility
are examined below:
<p>
<b>Sexually-Transmitted Diseases (STDs)</b> -- The Alan Guttmacher
Institute estimates that between 100,000 and 150,000 women become
infertile each year as a result of an STD that has resulted in
pelvic inflammatory disease. Thus, of the 2.3 million U.S. couples
who are infertile, 15 to 30 percent are infertile or unable to
conceive as a result of an STD.[6] Furthermore, while the rate of
infertility remained about the same from 1967 to 1982 at 2.4 million
couples (or one couple in every seven), infertility among couples
aged 20-24 increased from 4 percent in 1965 to 11 percent in 1982.[7]
It is likely that a good portion of this increase in early-age
infertility is directly attributable to sexually-transmitted diseases.
<p>
<b>Delayed Marriage and/or Childbearing</b> -- Data shows that
more people are delaying marriage and postponing childbearing
until older ages. For example, the proportion of first-time brides
who were between 25 and 39 years of age rose from 11 percent in
1970 to 41 percent in 1990.[8] In addition, the percentage of women
reaching age 35 who were still childless increased from 15 percent
in 1980 to 21 percent in 1991.[9] These statistics are significant
because age is positively associated with elevated risks of infertility
and miscarriage.[10]
<p></ul>
Because prospective adoptive couples greatly outnumber available
adoptable children, there exist long waiting lists for children,
regardless of age, race, or &quot;special needs.&quot; Consider
the following:
<ul><p>
<li>Of the 51,157 American children who were adopted in 1986 (the
latest available published data on domestic adoptions by the NCFA),
approximately one-half (24,589) were adoptions of healthy infants
(under 2 years of age) of all races and ethnic backgrounds. The
remainder were adoptions of older children or children with &quot;special
needs&quot; (physical, mental or emotional disabilities, being
part of a sibling group, etc.).[11]
<p>
<li>Babies, regardless of medical problems, are in particularly
high demand. There are waiting lists of couples who would like
to adopt infants with Downs Syndrome or spina bifida. The National
Downs Syndrome Adoption Exchange reports they have more than 100
approved families waiting to adopt children with Downs Syndrome.
There are also a large number of couples who would like to adopt
terminally-ill babies, including babies with AIDS.[12]
<p>
<li>In addition to the 50,000 domestic adoptions each year, American
couples or individuals adopt several thousand foreign-born children.
Begun first as a solution to emergency situations in foreign countries,
these adoptions have now become an important adoption alternative.
</ul><p>
<center><h4>Number of foreign adoptions by year, 1973-1994:[13]</h4>
<pre width=132>
<b>1973   1974   1975   1976    1977   1978   1979   1980   1981   1982   1983</b>  
4,323  5,446  6,290   7,051  6,854  5,652  4,864  5,139  4,868  5,749  7,127  
<p>
<b>1984   1985   1986   1987    1988   1989   1990   1991   1992   1993   1994</b>  
8,327  9,286  9,945  10,097  9,120  7,948  7,093  9,008  6,536  7,348  8,195  
</pre></center>
<p>
The numbers of foreign adoptions per year does not follow a recognizable
trend because intercountry adoptions are driven by supply. For
example, the Korean government has been on the front lines in
facilitating adoption. As a result, thousands of Korean children
were adopted by American citizens, accounting for the swell in
intercountry adoptions during the mid-1980s.[14] But even when foreign
governments fail to facilitate adoption, the demand for children
remains high. For example, after it aired a story on abandoned
Romanian infants, ABC-TV's &quot;20/20&quot; reported that it
received over 25,000 self-addressed stamped envelopes from individuals
wanting to adopt Romanian orphans.[15]
<p>
The &quot;adoption demand,&quot; though a large problem, could
<I>theoretically</I> be erased or at least drastically reduced
if more pregnant women chose to adoption rather than abortion
or if more unwed mothers chose adoption rather than single parenting.
However, until the adoption option is chosen by more of these
mothers in <I>reality</I>, many of these couples' desires to adopt
children will remain unfulfilled.
<p>
-- 12/19/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p><hr><p>
